1
00:00:00,083 --> 00:00:06,208
Of course, I remember the prison days,
and I remember the people I lived with

2
00:00:06,958 --> 00:00:09,708
It was one of the worst periods of my life that I lived here, with them

3
00:00:10,291 --> 00:00:14,125
It was... I don’t even know how to describe it to you

4
00:00:14,791 --> 00:00:18,250
I was released before them, and I wished they
had been released after me, but they weren’t

5
00:00:21,250 --> 00:00:26,166
Interviewer: You mentioned people who were executed.
What were their names, and who were they to you?

6
00:00:27,166 --> 00:00:32,208
They were death’s companions, and we were all destined for death

7
00:00:33,041 --> 00:00:35,458
One of them was Harith al-Hajj Abd, one of my relatives

8
00:00:36,041 --> 00:00:41,000
And Faisal Saad Rajoub, a young man from Homs, from Bab al-Sebaa

9
00:00:41,708 --> 00:00:44,833
And Khaled al-Alou, a young man from the city of Tabqa

10
00:00:45,541 --> 00:00:53,166
And Alaa, a young man from southern Rural Aleppo who
came here for a visit, and after a week he was detained

11
00:00:54,208 --> 00:00:59,083
And there were young men whose voices I used to hear from the
al-Boukhamees clan, from Mansoura, from the al-Hateel family

12
00:00:59,833 --> 00:01:05,208
I read their writings and loved them for the sake
of God in prison without ever seeing them

13
00:01:05,333 --> 00:01:09,541
I used to communicate with them, and I
wished I could see them outside, not here

14
00:01:10,666 --> 00:01:16,958
We all had hope of getting out,
but Alaa felt he would never leave

15
00:01:17,250 --> 00:01:20,875
He was afraid of that, even though we kept
reassuring him that he would be released from here

16
00:01:21,791 --> 00:01:26,583
And Faisal Saad Rajoub asked me to deliver a message to his mother

17
00:01:27,333 --> 00:01:32,250
That he had tried as much as he could,
even to the point of death, just to see her

18
00:01:32,333 --> 00:01:34,583
Because he hadn’t seen his mother for more than five years

19
00:01:35,333 --> 00:01:37,250
And all that was to reach her, but he never did

20
00:01:38,333 --> 00:01:40,583
Interviewer: Where was Faisal that he couldn’t reach her?

21
00:01:40,875 --> 00:01:45,375
Faisal was trapped in Homs, and his family had left the city

22
00:01:46,166 --> 00:01:49,708
He stayed there under siege for two or three years

23
00:01:50,458 --> 00:01:53,166
Then he left, but he was imprisoned by the Assad regime for a year

24
00:01:54,291 --> 00:01:58,791
After that, he returned here, and he intended to go to Jordan

25
00:01:59,708 --> 00:02:01,541
He stayed in Daraa for some time, but couldn’t leave

26
00:02:01,625 --> 00:02:04,125
His family contacted him and told him,
We’re going to Turkey, you must come

27
00:02:04,208 --> 00:02:07,250
So he could go to Turkey to meet them,
since he hadn’t seen them for five years

28
00:02:08,333 --> 00:02:13,833
When he entered ISIS-controlled areas, someone
recognized him—a man who had been with the Free Army

29
00:02:14,625 --> 00:02:18,458
That man caught him and said that the
battalion he belonged to was now in Idlib

30
00:02:18,583 --> 00:02:22,791
He said he was going to rejoin it, and
that’s when they accused him of that charge
